Use `JsonParser` from [jackson-core][1].

It provides api to read token by token from input stream.

Sample json

```json
{
    &quot;employees&quot; : [
        {
            &quot;empNo&quot;:10001,
            &quot;birthDate&quot;:&quot;02 September 1953&quot;,
            &quot;firstName&quot;:&quot;Georgi&quot;,
            &quot;lastName&quot;:&quot;Facello&quot;,
            &quot;gender&quot;:&quot;M&quot;,
            &quot;hireDate&quot;:&quot;26 June 1986&quot;
        }
        ...
    ]
}
```

Following are some cods with explanations for parsing above json response.

```java
// Create a parser from the response input stream
JsonParser jsonParser = objectMapper.getFactory().createParser(response.getBody());
    
    // Some condition checking, basically checking the response having `{`
    if(jsonParser.nextToken() == JsonToken.START_OBJECT) {
        // Checking the response having the field `&quot;employees&quot;`
        if(jsonParser.nextFieldName() == &quot;employees&quot;) {
            // Checking the response having the token `[`
            if(jsonParser.nextToken() == JsonToken.START_ARRAY) {
                // Loop until `]` found
			    while(jsonParser.nextToken() != JsonToken.END_ARRAY) {
                    // Extract domain object
				    Employee employee = jsonParser.readValueAs(Employee.class);
					// Do whatever with the domain object.
				}
			}
		}
	}

// Finally closing the parser.
jsonParser.close();
```

Above example is taken from [this blog post.][2]


